        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>New Haven</placeName>
                    <date>May 23, 1872.</date>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have addressed to you a copy of my book on <hi rend="underline">Corals and Coral Islands</hi>, and have commissioned my son, Edward S. Dana, to present himself along with it, and also to assure you of my unfailing esteem, and my admiration for your labors in behalf of Science.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> My son, having graduated at our University,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> goes to Europe to continue his studies in Science next autumn in Germany. In the meantime he looks forward to excursions during the summer in the Alps, as one means of benefiting his health, now somewhat impaired.</p>
<p>I was sorry that your sons did not visit New Haven when on this continent, and give me a chance to show my appreciation of their father.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">There is an annotated copy of Dana’s book on corals (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1765.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dana 1872</ref>) in the Darwin Library–CUL (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 179–80).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">E. S. Dana graduated from Yale University in 1870; J. D. Dana was professor of geology and mineralogy there (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1727.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DAB</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">George Howard and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> visited the United States in 1871 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7867.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Asa Gray, 16 July [1871]</ref>).</note>
